1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:25,751
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:25,951 --> 00:00:30,015
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,060 --> 00:00:45,554
So this evening, I just want to go over the technique a little bit that we're actually practicing, especially for those for whom it's quite new or completely new.

4
00:00:46,415 --> 00:00:51,402
And then to look at what the Buddha means by right awareness.

5
00:00:53,051 --> 00:00:59,100
And a quick look at the hindrances, what stops us to get this right awareness.

6
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:04,868
And then finally the three characteristics, you know, what is it we're supposed to be investigating after all.

7
00:01:06,992 --> 00:01:14,201
So a technique, remember, is to try to get us into a certain place.

8
00:01:14,602 --> 00:01:17,727
The technique itself doesn't produce anything.

9
00:01:17,858 --> 00:01:21,644
It's not the technique that allows insights to come.

10
00:01:21,903 --> 00:01:33,924
The insights, whatever they come, is always achieved by the intuitive intelligence that is the active part of awareness.

11
00:01:33,944 --> 00:01:35,365
So awareness has two sides.

12
00:01:35,966 --> 00:01:38,010
It has a receptive side,

13
00:01:38,378 --> 00:01:48,608
of awareness, what we would in English call awareness, and an active side of grasping the situation in its fullness.

14
00:01:49,670 --> 00:01:53,573
This intuitive awareness is working for us all the time.

15
00:01:53,614 --> 00:02:03,325
Every time in ordinary daily life, you know, you have a sudden brainwave or you hear a scratch and then you think, what could that be?

16
00:02:03,364 --> 00:02:06,207
And then you realize, oh, that's the cat.

17
00:02:07,757 --> 00:02:13,930
All that is part and parcel of this intuitive intelligence.

18
00:02:13,949 --> 00:02:16,032
And it's not to be confused with the intellect.

19
00:02:16,533 --> 00:02:18,056
It uses the intellect.

20
00:02:18,638 --> 00:02:21,223
The intellect itself is not intelligence.

21
00:02:22,806 --> 00:02:24,348
But I don't want to get into all that.

22
00:02:25,729 --> 00:02:44,784
just want to get first of all into the actual technique so the intellect which is a collection of these concepts and ideas that we have views opinions and so on is always a product of our history yeah

23
00:02:45,658 --> 00:02:49,789
It's always a way in which we can remember things.

24
00:02:50,331 --> 00:02:59,195
So even at the simplest level of an orange, you must have had lots of experiences with oranges and you have this concept of an orange.

25
00:02:59,664 --> 00:03:06,298
So somehow we have to release this awareness from its confusion with the intellect especially.

26
00:03:07,379 --> 00:03:09,203
It's our biggest enemy, thinking.

27
00:03:11,127 --> 00:03:17,860
So this technique is actually drawing the intellect down to a single, simple, concrete word.

28
00:03:18,548 --> 00:03:21,391
So you're not thinking about anything.

29
00:03:21,991 --> 00:03:25,776
The intellect is there, as it were, pushing you towards the object.

30
00:03:26,557 --> 00:03:36,730
So if you've got pain in the knee, for instance, a bit of discomfort in the knees, the word pain might come to mind to describe what you're experiencing or aching.

31
00:03:37,551 --> 00:03:40,514
And you just keep repeating that pain, pain, ache, ache.

32
00:03:40,756 --> 00:03:43,579
But your attention is not on the word.

33
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:45,020
It's not on the concept.

34
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:46,782
It's on the actual sensations.

35
00:03:48,637 --> 00:04:01,162
Now, when some people use this technique, they find the word is so strong, so obvious in front of them, they can't seem to feel anything or they barely feel something because the word is so strong.

36
00:04:01,402 --> 00:04:10,341
Now, what that is mirroring back to the meditator is that this confusion of awareness with intellect is very strong.

37
00:04:10,793 --> 00:04:11,514
Yeah.

38
00:04:11,533 --> 00:04:17,886
So somehow you've got to keep looking through the word, over the word, behind the word.

39
00:04:17,906 --> 00:04:23,355
You've got to keep pointing the attention to what it is you're actually experiencing.

40
00:04:24,677 --> 00:04:33,274
And what that does is it draws us down beyond the intellect with all its opinions and concepts and all that.

41
00:04:33,793 --> 00:04:40,663
to direct experience, which is, of course, the sensations to do with pain, sensations in the knee.

42
00:04:41,824 --> 00:04:47,874
So the word has to approximate what you're actually experiencing.

43
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:51,379
It's no good saying, if you've got a pain in the knee, banana, banana.

44
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:54,803
That's not going to really help you focus in on the pain.

45
00:04:55,264 --> 00:04:59,110
It's got to be something which is relevant to what you're experiencing.

46
00:04:59,089 --> 00:05:24,387
and it must be done at a rate which is keeping the intellect occupied or else it'll shoot off on maybe i should move maybe i shouldn't move should i move now maybe it just goes on and on and on so you've got to close that down with this very simple word so whatever you're doing if you can find a word and then draw your attention to what you're actually experiencing

47
00:05:25,026 --> 00:05:31,795
then that, of course, is releasing this awareness from its delusion of thinking that it is the intellect.

48
00:05:33,137 --> 00:05:34,658
And that's the same with imagination.

49
00:05:34,879 --> 00:05:36,961
The imagination and intellect work together.

50
00:05:37,362 --> 00:05:44,891
There's always an image comes with a concept, unless the concept is entirely abstract, like liberty or whatnot.

51
00:05:45,783 --> 00:05:56,730
Okay, so the danger is of course that it becomes a sort of mantra, you know, it's just sort of working in the background and it's losing that ability to point the awareness.

52
00:05:57,430 --> 00:06:02,322
The Mahasi himself talked about throwing a stone at bottles on a wall.

53
00:06:02,302 --> 00:06:05,026
So your eye is on the bottle, right?

54
00:06:05,286 --> 00:06:06,148
Not on the stone.

55
00:06:06,228 --> 00:06:07,449
It's not on your hand, is it?

56
00:06:07,951 --> 00:06:19,447
Yeah, it's actually on the bottle, you see, and you're throwing and what the stone is doing or what your intention of hitting that that bottle is, it's putting your attention directly on the bottle.

57
00:06:20,267 --> 00:06:21,470
So it's the same with this.

58
00:06:21,829 --> 00:06:27,218
You've got this ache in the knee and your attention wants to be right there with the ache.

59
00:06:27,817 --> 00:06:29,019
OK, so

60
00:06:30,281 --> 00:06:35,930
You have to use the word to get closer to what it is you're experiencing.

61
00:06:38,134 --> 00:06:47,509
Now, the technique itself is to get us beyond the technique.

62
00:06:47,528 --> 00:06:56,322
So it's drawing us to a concentration whereby we are just aware of the sensation of actually what's happening.

63
00:06:56,793 --> 00:07:03,380
So if you think about it, if I have an ache in my knee and I say pain, there's two consciousnesses there.

64
00:07:03,560 --> 00:07:10,548
There's one where I'm receiving this information about pain, and the second one is actually giving it a name.

65
00:07:11,269 --> 00:07:13,351
So there's restlessness in the mind.

66
00:07:13,992 --> 00:07:23,644
So by constantly making that effort to drive the attention towards the pain, time begins to collapse.

67
00:07:24,704 --> 00:07:35,584
And there'll come a point of what we might call absorption, where there's no time to note because you're completely absorbed into feeling the sensation of pain.

68
00:07:36,665 --> 00:07:37,968
That's what it's leading us towards.

69
00:07:38,329 --> 00:07:39,891
Now that doesn't come easy, right?

70
00:07:41,295 --> 00:07:43,317
You can't sit down and just get that.

71
00:07:43,598 --> 00:07:46,964
You have to keep working at it very slowly, very patiently.

72
00:07:47,552 --> 00:07:52,742
And it might only come in a little blip or a little blob before you're out of it again.

73
00:07:53,262 --> 00:08:05,545
But at least it manifests to the meditator that there is a level of concentration, a level of focus where you are completely involved in the object.

74
00:08:06,689 --> 00:08:23,365
and at that point of course the sense of self will disappear because self is also a reflection and with it a sense of time time and self always arise together so those moments of just being the knowing

75
00:08:23,345 --> 00:08:27,348
of what you're actually experiencing are precious little moments.

76
00:08:27,528 --> 00:08:30,351
And this intuitive awareness is very clear.

77
00:08:31,072 --> 00:08:36,738
It's not being fogged over by emotions or by images or by intellect.

78
00:08:37,577 --> 00:08:40,061
And that's when little insights come.

79
00:08:40,341 --> 00:08:44,504
Now, of course, there are occasionally a person might have a big insight.

80
00:08:44,825 --> 00:08:52,913
But generally speaking, they're small little insights which accumulate over time and change our attitude to things.

81
00:08:59,136 --> 00:09:06,724
So the real message there is to really, really put effort into that noting, you see.

82
00:09:07,303 --> 00:09:11,206
If you slacken on the noting, the noting becomes a mantra.

83
00:09:11,248 --> 00:09:14,529
See, rising, falling, rising, falling.

84
00:09:14,990 --> 00:09:19,634
And then you're off to Costa del Sol.

85
00:09:20,154 --> 00:09:23,857
And then when you come back, you can hear yourself saying, rising, falling.

86
00:09:25,379 --> 00:09:29,143
So you've taught yourself to say rising and falling, which is absolutely useless.

87
00:09:29,562 --> 00:09:34,571
So it's going to be something really direct and pointed.

88
00:09:36,453 --> 00:09:37,856
And the other thing is you get bored.

89
00:09:38,017 --> 00:09:39,480
So you have to be careful of boredom.

90
00:09:40,081 --> 00:09:44,187
So if you get bored, that's your object of meditation, right?

91
00:09:44,388 --> 00:09:46,451
That's when you say, oh, this is boredom.

92
00:09:46,471 --> 00:09:47,113
That's interesting.

93
00:09:47,653 --> 00:09:49,837
And you move towards it and you feel it.

94
00:09:50,097 --> 00:09:53,224
And your noting word is boredom, boredom, right?

95
00:09:54,232 --> 00:10:05,346
So it is this constant effort, see, and if you find yourself getting tight, so just relax, you know, you can open the eyes, just relax a bit and come back to the practice.

96
00:10:05,366 --> 00:10:10,994
If you find yourself getting a bit lazy about it, then, you know, talk to yourself.

97
00:10:11,354 --> 00:10:12,274
Stop this immediately.

98
00:10:12,414 --> 00:10:13,976
Let's get back to the practice.

99
00:10:15,058 --> 00:10:16,139
Don't let yourself off.

100
00:10:17,841 --> 00:10:19,263
So that's the noting, right?

101
00:10:19,864 --> 00:10:31,615
And it is, in a way, specific to the Mahasi technique, although I did hear of a Zen teacher, Maezumi Roshi, who used to work in America, used to use noting.

102
00:10:33,697 --> 00:10:37,802
Now, the fact is, of course, that this labeling, this noting is going on anyway.

103
00:10:37,822 --> 00:10:38,403
That's the point.

104
00:10:39,063 --> 00:10:45,029
Even if you're not aware of it, as soon as you experience something, you're putting a label on it, OK?

105
00:10:47,423 --> 00:10:49,467
Now, the next thing is going slow.

106
00:10:49,528 --> 00:10:51,111
Well, that's pretty straightforward.

107
00:10:51,392 --> 00:10:53,255
It's just the slower you go, the more you see.

108
00:10:53,437 --> 00:10:54,558
It's as simple as that.

109
00:10:55,360 --> 00:11:03,019
And by slowing things down, you begin to see minute movements, minute movements.

110
00:11:03,336 --> 00:11:11,988
There's a lovely incident in one of the commentaries called the Visuddhimagga, the path of purification, which is a sort of medieval text.

111
00:11:12,687 --> 00:11:19,756
And it's a great spiritual manual, but you wouldn't want to read it from page one to 1,500.

112
00:11:20,197 --> 00:11:21,499
You're driving potty.

113
00:11:22,120 --> 00:11:23,841
But it is a great encyclopedia.

114
00:11:23,861 --> 00:11:26,205
You just open it, and it'll tell you something.

115
00:11:26,590 --> 00:11:33,410
And it talks about this particular teacher who was giving a talk and whatnot, and he suddenly raised his hand and stopped.

116
00:11:33,761 --> 00:11:35,063
and then put his hand back down.

117
00:11:35,745 --> 00:11:37,447
And all the students said, what happened there?

118
00:11:37,967 --> 00:11:38,928
What happened?

119
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:42,052
He said, I didn't note the intention to raise the hand.

120
00:11:42,594 --> 00:11:43,956
So that's how fine it can get.

121
00:11:44,355 --> 00:11:56,832
And if you think of how many automatic movements we make, which are perfectly ethical, opening a door, closing a door, switching a light on, switching it off.

122
00:11:56,812 --> 00:12:07,562
And we don't see that every action we make, whether it's a thought pattern, a pattern of speech or an action, always begins with an intention.

123
00:12:08,263 --> 00:12:11,986
And that's so important because that's the only choice we have.

124
00:12:12,346 --> 00:12:14,948
Once you're committed, that's it, you're done for.

125
00:12:15,549 --> 00:12:18,211
So it's a case of catching the intention.

126
00:12:18,633 --> 00:12:24,977
And when you can see the intention, the desire to do something, that's your moment of choice.

127
00:12:24,998 --> 00:12:25,599
Will I do it?

128
00:12:25,619 --> 00:12:26,820
Will I not do it?

129
00:12:26,799 --> 00:12:52,942
yeah that's the only bit of little bit of freedom that we have you might say so going slow really helps us to see this the role of intention and with it coupled with it of course the role of action that once you empower it you've done something so that's why the buddha says action the will is action you can't separate the will from the action

130
00:12:52,923 --> 00:12:58,979
It's a bit like, you know, if you throw a stone into the air, you can't separate the force from the stone.

131
00:12:59,961 --> 00:13:00,602
You can't take it.

132
00:13:00,643 --> 00:13:02,548
Well, this is the force and this is the stone.

133
00:13:03,772 --> 00:13:06,317
They're both completely at one with each other.

134
00:13:06,779 --> 00:13:08,804
So it's the same with an action and a will.

135
00:13:11,283 --> 00:13:26,364
And I think you'll find that if you get the habit of stopping, and this also in daily life, you know, to stop after you've done something, after a phone call or anything, you do get more of a sense of presence, you know, that you've been here most of the day, that you've been here most of the time.

136
00:13:27,085 --> 00:13:30,789
It really does keep bringing you back into the present moment.

137
00:13:33,192 --> 00:13:38,320
And so this going slow, that's the third part, this noting intentions.

138
00:13:39,193 --> 00:14:09,149
and to understand karma meaning action and of course the product you know to be aware that whenever we do something there's always going to be you know a product from it there's always going to be a consequence right so those are the three things that we say mark out the Mahasi technique as such noting going slow and noting intentions okay

139
00:14:10,716 --> 00:14:15,464
So I'll remind you of that, hopefully, if I remember, at the end of the talk.

140
00:14:16,826 --> 00:14:21,854
So the next task, of course, is to understand what the Buddha means by this right awareness.

141
00:14:23,336 --> 00:14:25,458
A bank robber has awareness.

142
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:28,764
Somebody who's fraudulent has awareness.

143
00:14:29,063 --> 00:14:31,908
Awareness is with us virtually all the time.

144
00:14:32,649 --> 00:14:34,993
Even in sleep, there's a sense of awareness.

145
00:14:35,052 --> 00:14:37,596
I mean, otherwise you wouldn't hear the alarm clock.

146
00:14:37,777 --> 00:14:39,659
It's there in a residual sense.

147
00:14:40,197 --> 00:14:46,686
So when the Buddha talks about right awareness, he's talking about something quite specific.

148
00:14:47,486 --> 00:14:48,970
And it has two qualities.

149
00:14:49,549 --> 00:14:52,975
It has the quality of coming from a place of not knowing.

150
00:14:53,576 --> 00:14:58,803
In other words, not knowing, not coming from a place of I know, I'm sure.

151
00:14:59,644 --> 00:15:05,293
As soon as you do that, then whatever you experience will only be something that you agree with.

152
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,330
only something that you've already imagined.

153
00:15:08,850 --> 00:15:15,417
So this would be a classic terrible mistake about, say, the Nibbāna.

154
00:15:15,437 --> 00:15:26,047
So if you have an idea of Nibbāna, then if you attain it, you'll be definitely deluded because it's not imaginable.

155
00:15:27,668 --> 00:15:32,293
It's gone beyond imagination.

156
00:15:34,450 --> 00:15:41,658
The awareness has to be clear, you see, and it has to be, when it becomes clear, it becomes original, right?

157
00:15:41,677 --> 00:15:44,900
And this is why in Zen they talk about original mind.

158
00:15:45,461 --> 00:15:47,844
What they mean is original awareness.

159
00:15:48,764 --> 00:15:51,427
And the example I use is of a little child.

160
00:15:52,009 --> 00:16:02,820
So everybody's seen a three-year-old, especially, you know, round about that age, three, four, five, and they see for the first time something like a spider.

161
00:16:02,799 --> 00:16:32,638
and you can see their eyes glue on it you know they just they just stick on it and the world disappears and the other thing that happens is the jaw drops and they look gauntless you know and our job as adults is to wake them up which is a terrible thing actually and so there they are glued onto this spider and then after they've received enough information they always turn around to mummy or daddy and say what is it you see then they get this label spider okay

162
00:16:33,596 --> 00:16:37,644
So now, the next time they see a spider, they rejoice.

163
00:16:37,684 --> 00:16:38,807
They say, spider, spider.

164
00:16:39,327 --> 00:16:41,633
And mummy and daddy say, very good.

165
00:16:42,193 --> 00:16:42,413
See?

166
00:16:44,038 --> 00:16:47,063
But the problem is, they haven't seen this other spider.

167
00:16:47,244 --> 00:16:53,817
What they've seen is a concept of the idea of a spider, which they're already plunking on to this new spider.

168
00:16:55,096 --> 00:16:57,320
In other words, they've lost the original mind.

169
00:16:57,421 --> 00:17:04,535
They've lost that original way of receiving information before concepts get in the way.

170
00:17:06,077 --> 00:17:17,019
So our job is to get back to that point where there are no more concepts or ideas coming in to distort the way we are looking at things.

171
00:17:18,923 --> 00:17:21,286
That doesn't mean to say that you lose the concept.

172
00:17:21,806 --> 00:17:22,727
It's always there.

173
00:17:23,268 --> 00:17:25,309
In fact, it's rather useful in daily life.

174
00:17:25,691 --> 00:17:28,193
But in Vipassana, it's a bit of a pain.

175
00:17:29,474 --> 00:17:40,386
So if we have that concept of a child, with the glued eyes and the jaw relaxed, the reason the jaw is relaxed is because there's no thinking.

176
00:17:41,729 --> 00:17:48,036
In your meditation, you might find that when you're thinking, you might just catch these little movements on your tongue.

177
00:17:48,521 --> 00:17:51,526
caused by the thinking pattern.

178
00:17:52,186 --> 00:18:13,758
So when the jaw is relaxed and the tongue is relaxed and the eyes are fixed, you see, when you take that inwardly into yourself and you're just observing, just feeling, just experiencing, then we're getting to original mind or better, in my language, pure awareness.

179
00:18:15,961 --> 00:18:17,262
Intuitive awareness, remember.

180
00:18:18,137 --> 00:18:41,226
IA not AI there's nothing artificial about it this is the real thing so that's that's this intuitive awareness and this really comes about through the story of the Buddha which many of you will will already know but remember that when he left home he was in a bit of a crisis he was in what we would call an existential crisis

181
00:18:41,205 --> 00:19:07,145
i mean it's put down as you know these five messengers where he sees somebody very very sick very old a corpse and somebody sitting under a tree suggesting that there might be a way out of this sickness aging and death his first two teachers teach him how to attain beautiful mental states and these you find in all religions that's not a you know devotional religions especially

182
00:19:07,919 --> 00:19:10,982
through repetitive prayer, mantra, etc.

183
00:19:11,203 --> 00:19:13,846
Even music, repetitive music.

184
00:19:15,809 --> 00:19:21,538
And of course, when he comes out of those absorptions, well, he's back to being anxious and depressed again.

185
00:19:22,298 --> 00:19:23,359
So it didn't really work.

186
00:19:23,740 --> 00:19:37,420
The next thing he tried was, of course, this very severe asceticism, which it's suggested he was following the Nigantha, the leader of the Jains, the Jain leader.

187
00:19:37,940 --> 00:19:47,136
And in Jainism, the understanding is that the body is the expression of your bad karma.

188
00:19:47,877 --> 00:19:51,964
And if you can get rid of the body, the soul would rise naturally to heaven.

189
00:19:52,707 --> 00:20:02,344
So the Jain reduces their body and it's considered to be a saintly thing to slowly starve oneself to death.

190
00:20:02,576 --> 00:20:08,825
And many elderly people in Jainism actually will do that, letting go of the body.

191
00:20:09,605 --> 00:20:15,573
And I would have thought that if that's done properly, that's quite a spiritual journey, letting go of the body.

192
00:20:16,794 --> 00:20:21,980
But he said he got so thin that he could hold his spine through his stomach.

193
00:20:22,181 --> 00:20:25,884
So if you try that, you'll see how thin he was.

194
00:20:27,568 --> 00:20:30,532
And he said it was just more suffering.

195
00:20:31,272 --> 00:20:35,038
So when he comes out from that, you can imagine that he's quite despairing.

196
00:20:35,218 --> 00:20:40,605
I mean, he's now been to all the teachers, he's been to all the discussions, etc.

197
00:20:41,246 --> 00:20:42,487
And he's stuck.

198
00:20:42,787 --> 00:20:43,969
He doesn't see a way out.

199
00:20:44,910 --> 00:20:49,715
And that's when he is sitting by the road and a woman comes who's called Sujata.

200
00:20:49,736 --> 00:20:51,877
I think it was a name given to her later on.

201
00:20:51,938 --> 00:20:55,702
It just means a happy birth, an auspicious birth.

202
00:20:56,019 --> 00:21:02,275
and offers him some sweetmeats that she was going to offer to a local shrine.

203
